# Code Quality (Imported 1-5)

These are the project-wide code quality rules for all agents.

## 1) Read the manual and follow vendor best practices

- Before implementing, check reliable official docs for the framework, package, or platform involved.
- Prefer implementation patterns intended by the vendor/maintainers over ad-hoc shortcuts.

## 2) Keep files short; split by nested structure

- No single source file should exceed 250 lines where practical.
- If a component/module grows, split into smaller focused pieces.
- Use TypeScript by default for all application code; do not add new `.js` files in `src/`.

## 3) Vue components use recursive folder nesting

- Parent and child components should not live flat in one folder when composition grows.
- Use one folder per feature/component root.
- Keep the main component file at folder root, with `components/` for direct children.
- If a child has children, repeat the same pattern recursively.
- Use `assets/` for styles shared by that component subtree.

## 4) Non-Vue code uses block-based module structure

- For stores/services/api/logic blocks, use one folder per block with a clear entry file.
- Split internals by role (for example `handlers/`, `services/`, `adapters/`, `utils/`) as complexity grows.
- Keep each file short and single-purpose; split further as needed.

## 5) Apply consistently across the app

- Each top-level view/feature should have a clear folder boundary.
- Keep shared/global styles in common assets location; keep feature-specific styles inside feature folders.
- Keep shared logic centralized (composables/shared utils/common modules).
- Keep functions small and focused; avoid long mixed-responsibility files and functions.

## 6) Enforce strict TypeScript

- Keep strict compiler settings enabled (`strict`, `noUncheckedIndexedAccess`, `noImplicitOverride`).
- Prefer explicit interfaces/types for domain data and component contracts.
- Use enums or union types for constrained values (for example route names, statuses, or modes).
- Avoid `any`; if unavoidable, use `unknown` first and narrow safely.

## 7) Type Vue components deliberately

- Use `<script setup lang="ts">` in Vue SFCs that have script logic.
- Type reactive/computed values when inference is weak or route/meta data is involved.
- Extract reusable TS types into feature-level type files when data shapes are shared.

## 8) Keep TS quality verifiable

- Ensure the project has a working `type-check` script and run it after substantial edits.
- Keep Vite/router/app entrypoints in TypeScript where supported by the toolchain.
